\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Physically Secure Locations & Perimeters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The perimeter of any physically secure location containing critical IT infrastructure or processing CJI shall be prominently posted and structurally separated from non-secure locations by physical controls (e.g.,
 locked doors,
 card readers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Information system devices shall be positioned to prevent unauthorized individuals from accessing or visually observing CJI or sensitive administrative sessions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1.1 Physical Access Control Procedures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Elko County shall maintain physical access audit logs for all physically secure IT locations.
 Audit logs shall record all access events and shall be retained in accordance with applicable Nevada retention schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Keys,
 key fobs,
 access cards,
 and combination codes shall be stored securely when not in use and shall not be shared among personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Combinations and keys shall be changed,
 and access cards shall be deactivated and reissued,
 whenever:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(a) a key is lost or a combination is believed to have been compromised;
 or 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(b) an individual possessing a key,
 combination,
 or unescorted access credential is transferred to a role not requiring access or is separated from the County.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Physical Access Authorizations & Visitor Control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Elko County shall develop,
 approve,
 and maintain an access list of authorized individuals permitted to access physically secure IT locations.
 This list shall be reviewed and updated at least annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Physical access credential issuance,
 modification,
 and revocation for all secure IT facilities shall follow the personnel onboarding and offboarding procedures defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Upon notification of personnel separation or role change,
 physical access credentials (including keycards,
 key fobs,
 and combination codes) shall be revoked on the same timelines established for logical access revocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The County must maintain a visitor control log detailing the names,
 organizations,
 dates,
 entry/exit times,
 and forms of identification used to authenticate every visitor accessing a physically secure location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Visitors must be escorted by authorized personnel at all times within secure areas.
 When the escort involves vendor or contractor personnel performing maintenance on systems that process,
 store,
 or transmit Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 the designated escort shall be fully cleared and technically qualified to supervise the specific maintenance activity being performed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Visitor access records shall be reviewed at least quarterly.
 Reviews shall assess whether access authorizations remain current and appropriate for organizational mission and business functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Anomalies identified during visitor access record reviews —
 including unauthorized access patterns,
 missing records,
 or entries outside of authorized access periods —
 shall be reported to personnel with physical and environmental protection responsibilities and to personnel with information security responsibilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Retention Mandate
\series default
:
 The visitor control log must be retained for a minimum period of three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year to which the log pertains,
 in strict compliance with Nevada LRDA 20071279.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Monitoring Physical Access & Camera Surveillance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Elko County shall monitor physical access to facilities where information systems reside to detect and respond to physical security incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Security cameras in server rooms and network closets shall be configured with motion detection.
 Upon detection of motion,
 the system shall automatically notify designated IT personnel via email during normal business hours.
 Motion events occurring outside of business hours shall generate a work order for IT staff follow-up on the next business day.
 Camera-based motion alerting satisfies the physical intrusion alarm requirement under CJIS PE-6(1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Physical access logs shall be reviewed at least quarterly and following any physical,
 environmental,
 or security-related incident involving CJI or systems used to process,
 store,
 or transmit CJI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The results of physical access log reviews and any physical security investigations shall be coordinated with the County's incident response capability in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Incident Response Policy Overview).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Retention Mandate:
 Security camera recordings strictly monitoring physical access shall be retained for a minimum of seven (7) days or for the period needed to review the recordings,
 whichever is longer,
 in strict compliance with Nevada LRDA 20071749.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
If camera footage captures an incident,
 breach,
 or legal event,
 the relevant segment of footage shall immediately be exported,
 reported in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Identification and Reporting Procedures),
 reclassified as an "Incident Report" or "Investigation Record," and retained according to the applicable Nevada retention schedules governing active investigations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Environmental Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fire Protection
\series default
:
 Facilities containing critical IT infrastructure must employ automatic fire suppression and/or detection systems.
 These systems shall be maintained and inspected annually.
 Fire detection systems shall be configured to automatically activate upon detection of fire conditions and to simultaneously notify designated organizational incident response personnel and local emergency responders without requiring manual intervention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Temperature and Humidity Controls
\series default
:
 Critical IT hardware facilities (e.g.,
 primary server rooms) shall maintain automated temperature and humidity controls to prevent environmental degradation of systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Water Damage Protection
\series default
:
 Master shutoff valves shall be identified and accessible.
 IT equipment shall be positioned or elevated to minimize risk from water damage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Power Equipment,
 Emergency Infrastructure,
 and Continuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Power Equipment and Cabling
\series default
:
 Power equipment and power cabling serving critical IT infrastructure shall be protected from physical damage and destruction.
 Cabling paths shall be identified,
 documented,
 and physically secured within locked conduits or restricted-access routing pathways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Shutoff
\series default
:
 Facilities housing critical IT infrastructure shall provide the capability to shut off power to all information systems in emergency situations.
 Emergency shutoff switches or devices shall be placed in locations readily accessible to authorized personnel.
 Emergency shutoff capability shall be protected from unauthorized or accidental activation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Power
\series default
:
 Critical IT facilities shall be equipped with an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) to provide near-instantaneous protection from power interruptions and to facilitate orderly system shutdown or transition to an alternate power source upon loss of primary power.
 UPS units shall be maintained in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 lifecycle standards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Lighting
\series default
:
 Critical IT facilities shall employ and maintain automatic emergency lighting that activates upon power outage or disruption.
 Emergency lighting shall cover emergency exits and evacuation routes within the facility.
\end_layout

